{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Despite that, the term LLM is still used a lot in publications, and has some overlap with the term \"foundation model\" [2], that is defined as \"[..] any model that is trained on broad data at scale and can be adapted (e.g., fine-tuned) to a wide range of downstream tasks\".",
    "In our work we refer to LLMs if the model has at least 100 billion parameters and works on text only (which excludes multimodal models).",
    "Examples for such models include Googles LaMDA [3] with 137B, Open AIs GPT-3 [4] with 175b and Nvidia's Megatron Turing NLG [5] with 540B parameters.One of the benefits of such models is that they are extremely versatile multi-task models.",
    "Furthermore, their zero-shot and few-shot performance on a large number of tasks is impressive.",
    "Since they are pretrained on text-completion mostly, they are also good for \"answering openended questions in natural language\" which is e.g."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
